question:
Determine the smallest non-negative integer $a$ that satisfies the congruences: \begin{align*}
&a\equiv 2\pmod 3,\\
&a\equiv 4\pmod 5,\\
&a\equiv 6\pmod 7,\\
&a\equiv 8\pmod 9.
\end{align*}

solution:
By the Binomial Theorem, we have  \begin{align*}
301^4 &= (3(100) + 1)^4\\
&= \binom40 \cdot 3^4 \cdot 100^4 \cdot 1^0 + \binom41 \cdot 3^3 \cdot 100^3 \cdot 1^1 \\
&\qquad\qquad+ \binom42 \cdot 3^2 \cdot 100^2 \cdot 1^2+ \binom43 \cdot 3^1 \cdot 100^1 \cdot 1^3 \\
&\qquad\qquad+ \binom44 \cdot 3^0 \cdot 100^0 \cdot 1^4.
\end{align*} All but the last two terms are divisible by $10000=100^2$, so we only have to consider the remainder when the last two terms are divided by 10,000. The last two terms are  \begin{align*}
\binom43 &\cdot 3^1 \cdot 100^1 \cdot 1^3 + \binom44 \cdot 3^0 \cdot 100^0 \cdot 1^4\\
&= 4 \cdot 3 \cdot 100 \cdot 1 + 1 \cdot 1 \cdot 1 \cdot 1\\
& = 1200 + 1 = \boxed{1201}.\end{align*}

There are $2^{10} = 1024$ ways to answer the questions on the true/false test. However, we can also compute the number of ways of answering the questions on the true/false test by using combinations; there are $\binom{10}{k}$ ways to answer $k$ of the questions on the test with a false, so we have: $$\binom{10}{0} + \binom{10}{1} + \cdots + \binom{10}{9} + \binom{10}{10} = 2^{10}.$$ The desired answer is \begin{align*}
&\binom{10}{3} + \binom{10}{4} + \cdots + \binom{10}{9} + \binom{10}{10} \\
=\text{ }&2^{10} - \binom{10}{0} - \binom{10}{1} - \binom{10}{2} = 1024 - 1 - 10 - 45 \\
=\text{ }&\boxed{968}.
\end{align*}

